      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation execution checklist completed by independent reviewer; boundary condition application verified against F1717 test setup drawings.",
      "rationale": "A documented simulation execution checklist was completed and independently reviewed. Boundary conditions (pin-pin fixture, displacement-controlled loading) were verified against ASTM F1717 test fixture drawings. Material property assignments were cross-checked against the material characterization dataset."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Linear elastic material model with contact interfaces appropriate for pre-yield loading regime; model assumptions documented and justified.",
      "rationale": "The FEA model employs linear elastic material models for titanium alloy components (Ti-6Al-4V, E = 114 GPa) with frictional contact (μ = 0.2) at the screw-rod interface. Given that the primary QoIs (stiffness, yield force) are assessed in the pre-yield regime, the linear elastic assumption is well-justified. Geometric nonlinearity is included via large-displacement formulation. Model form assumptions are documented in the modeling report MR-001."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from coupon testing of production-lot material; geometric dimensions from CMM measurements of test specimens.",
      "rationale": "Material elastic modulus and Poisson's ratio were determined from tensile coupon testing of production-lot Ti-6Al-4V material (n=5 coupons per batch). Geometric dimensions of the screw and rod were obtained from coordinate measuring machine (CMM) measurements of the actual test specimens. Input uncertainty was propagated through a Monte Carlo analysis (n=500 runs) to establish simulation uncertainty bounds."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 test constructs from production-representative lots; constructs assembled per clinical technique.",
      "rationale": "Eleven (N=11) test constructs were assembled from production-representative material lots by trained technicians following the clinical assembly technique. Constructs were distributed across two independent laboratories to assess inter-laboratory variability. Sample size exceeds the minimum requirement of N=10 for Medium model risk level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Testing conducted under at least two distinct loading rates or environmental conditions representative of the COU envelope.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single quasi-static displacement rate (5 mm/min) per ASTM F1717. While this condition is clinically representative of the worst-case static loading scenario, only a single test condition was evaluated. The achieved level of 2 falls below the required level of 3; this gap is acknowledged and accepted given that the single test condition represents the conservative bound for the COU."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA boundary conditions demonstrably equivalent to physical test setup; fixture geometry modeled explicitly.",
      "rationale": "The ASTM F1717 test fixture geometry (upper and lower fixtures, pin-pin boundary conditions, loading platen) was explicitly modeled in the FEA. Fixture stiffness was verified against separate fixture-only calibration tests. The 44 mm offset distance specified in F1717 was reproduced exactly in the simulation geometry. Equivalency between physical and computational boundary conditions is confirmed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison using E/uval metric; E/uval < 1.96 for all three primary QoIs.",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison was performed for all three primary QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) using the validation metric E/uval = (|E_sim - E_exp|) / sqrt(u_sim^2 + u_exp^2). All three E/uval values (0.84, 0.91, 0.67) fall below the acceptance threshold of 1.96, confirming adequate predictive accuracy across the QoI space."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) are directly linked to clinical failure modes and regulatory submission requirements.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs are directly specified in ASTM F1717 and are the primary metrics used in FDA 510(k) submissions for spinal fixation systems. Construct stiffness relates to load sharing with the vertebral column; yield force and force at 40 mm displacement characterize structural integrity under physiological loading. The QoIs are fully relevant to the COU decision."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation testing performed on the same device design, material lot, and loading configuration as the COU.",
      "rationale": "Validation testing was performed on the identical non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design, assembled with the same rod diameter and material as the COU device. The ASTM F1717 compression-bending configuration directly replicates the loading mode of interest. The validation activities are therefore highly relevant to the COU with no significant extrapolation required."
    }
